Definition 48 (Par on strategies). Given games $A$, $B$, $C$ and $D$, the par of strategies $\phi:A\multimap C$ and $\psi:B\multimap D$ is the subset $\phi\invamp\psi\subseteq P_{A\invamp B\multimap C\invamp D}^{\mathsf{Even}}$ defined by: $\phi\invamp\psi\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in P_{A% \invamp B\multimap C\invamp D}^{\mathsf{Even}}\mid\bm{s}\upharpoonright A,C\in% \phi,\bm{s}\upharpoonright B,D\in\psi\ \!\}$ where $\bm{s}\upharpoonright A,C$ (resp. $\bm{s}\upharpoonright B,D$) is the j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ that consists of moves $(\hat{a},\hat{b})\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}}$, $(\hat{c},\hat{d})\in M_{C}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{D}^{\mathsf{Init}}$, $a\in M_{A}$ and $c\in M_{C}$ (resp. $b\in M_{B}$ and $d\in M_{D}$) with the first two changed into $\hat{a}$ and $\hat{c}$ (resp. $\hat{b}$ and $\hat{d}$), respectively.
Definition 3 (LL$\bm{{}^{-}}$ and LLK$\bm{{}^{-}}$). The formal language of linear logic negative (LL$\bm{{}^{-}}$) is obtained from that of LL by discarding linear negation $(\_)^{\bot}$. The calculus LLK${\bm{{}^{-}}}$ for LL${}^{-}$ consists of the rules in Fig. 2, where $f(A_{1},A_{2},\dots,A_{k})\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}fA_{1},fA_% {2},\dots,fA_{k}$ for all $f\in\{\oc,\wn\}$.
Definition 16 (BiLSMCCs). A bi-liberalizable (BiL) SMCC is a NSC $\mathcal{C}=(\mathcal{C},\otimes,\top,\multimap,\oc)$ such that it has weak finite coproducts $(0,\oplus)$, and it is equipped with: • A lluf subBwLSMC $\sharp\mathcal{C}$ and a triple $(\invamp,\bot,\wn)$ such that $\top$ (resp. $\bot$) is terminal (resp. initial) in $\sharp\mathcal{C}$, $\sharp\mathcal{C}(A,\bot)=\mathcal{C}(A,\bot)$ and $\sharp\mathcal{C}(\top,B)=\mathcal{C}(\top,B)$ for all $A,B\in\mathcal{C}$, and $\sharp\mathcal{C}=(\sharp\mathcal{C},\invamp,\bot,\wn)$ is FwL with finite coproducts $(0,\oplus)$; • Natural transformations $\Omega$, $\Sigma$ and $\Pi$ in $\sharp\mathcal{C}$ (Lem. 13); • Natural isomorphisms (1) and (2) as well as $\displaystyle\wn(A\multimap B)$ $\displaystyle\cong\oc A\multimap\wn B$ $\displaystyle\neg A\oplus\neg B$ $\displaystyle\cong\neg(A\&B)$ (natural in $A,B\in\mathcal{C}$) in $\sharp\mathcal{C}$; • A distributive law $\Upsilon$ of $\oc$ over $\wn$.
Definition 34 (Linearity of strategies). A j-sequence $\bm{s}$ is linear, written $\mathsf{L}(\bm{s})$, if, for each even-length prefix $\bm{t}$ of $\bm{s}$, an initial move $q$ in $\bm{t}$ justifies exactly one question $q^{\prime}$ in $\bm{t}$, and the number of answers justified by $q^{\prime}$ equals that of answers justified by $q$ in $\bm{t}$. A strategy $\sigma:G$ is linear if $\forall\bm{s}\in\sigma.\ \!\mathsf{L}(\bm{s})$.
Definition 7 (BwLSMCs). A SMC $\mathcal{C}=(\mathcal{C},\otimes,\top)$ is backward liberalizable (BwL) if it has finite products $(1,\&)$ and is equipped with: • A comonad $\oc=(\oc,\epsilon,\delta)$ on $\mathcal{C}$ such that the canonical adjunction between $\mathcal{C}$ and the co-Kleisli category $\mathcal{C}_{\oc}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ over $\oc$ is monoidal; • Isomorphisms $\top\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\rightarrow}}\oc 1$ and $\oc A\otimes\oc B\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\rightarrow}}\oc(A\&B)$ natural in $A,B\in\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 40 (Tensor product of strategies [17, 18]). Given games $A$, $B$, $C$ and $D$, and strategies $\phi:A\multimap C$ and $\psi:B\multimap D$, the tensor (product) $\phi\otimes\psi$ of $\phi$ and $\psi$ is given by: $\phi\otimes\psi\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in\mathscr{L% }_{A\otimes B\multimap C\otimes D}\mid\bm{s}\upharpoonright A,C\in\phi,\bm{s}% \upharpoonright B,D\in\psi\ \!\}$ where $\bm{s}\upharpoonright A,C$ (resp. $\bm{s}\upharpoonright B,D$) is the j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ that consists of moves of $A$ or $C$ (resp. $B$ or $D$).
Definition 22 (J-subsequences). Let $G$ be an arena, and $\bm{s}\in\mathscr{J}_{G}$. A j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ is any $\bm{t}\in\mathscr{J}_{G}$ that satisfies: • $\bm{t}$ is a subsequence of $\bm{s}$, written $(\bm{s}(i_{1}),\bm{s}(i_{2}),\dots,\bm{s}(i_{|\bm{t}|}))$; • $\mathcal{J}_{\bm{t}}(\bm{s}(i_{r}))=\bm{s}(i_{l})$ iff there are occurrences $\bm{s}(j_{1}),\bm{s}(j_{2}),\dots,\bm{s}(j_{k})$ in $\bm{s}$ eliminated in $\bm{t}$ such that $\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(\bm{s}(i_{r}))=\bm{s}(j_{1})\wedge\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(% \bm{s}(j_{1}))=\bm{s}(j_{2})\dots\wedge\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(\bm{s}(j_{k-1}))=% \bm{s}(j_{k})\wedge\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(\bm{s}(j_{k}))=\bm{s}(i_{l})$.
Definition 53 (Why not monad). Given $A\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}$, strategies $\mathit{wst}_{A}:A\multimap\wn A$ and $\mathit{abs}_{A}:\wn\wn A\multimap\wn A$, called the waste and the absorption on $A$, respectively, are defined by: $\displaystyle\mathit{wst}_{A}$ $\displaystyle\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in P_{A% \multimap\wn A}^{\mathsf{Even}}\mid\forall\bm{t}\preceq\bm{s}.\ \!\mathsf{Even% }(\bm{t})\Rightarrow\bm{t}\upharpoonright A=\bm{t}\upharpoonright\wn A% \upharpoonright 0\ \!\}$ $\displaystyle\mathit{abs}_{A}$ $\displaystyle\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in P_{\wn\wn A% \multimap\wn A}^{\mathsf{Even}}\mid\forall\bm{t}\preceq\bm{s}.\ \!\mathsf{Even% }(\bm{t})$ $\displaystyle\Rightarrow\forall i,j\in\mathbb{N}.\ \!\bm{t}\upharpoonright\wn% \wn A\upharpoonright i\upharpoonright j=\bm{t}\upharpoonright\wn A% \upharpoonright\langle i,j\rangle\ \!\}$ where $\langle\_,\_\rangle$ is any fixed bijection $\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\rightarrow}}\mathbb{N}$. The why not monad is the monad $\wn=(\wn,\eta,\mu)$ on $\sharp\mathcal{LG}$, where: • The functor $\wn$ is given by $A\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}\mapsto\wn A\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}$, and $[\phi]\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}(A,B)\mapsto[\wn\phi]\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}(\wn A,% \wn B)$; • The components of the natural transformations $\eta:\mathit{id}_{\sharp\mathcal{LG}}\Rightarrow\wn$ and $\mu:\wn\wn\Rightarrow\wn$ on each $A\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}$ are given by $\eta_{A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}[\mathit{wst}_{A}]$ and $\mu_{A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}[\mathit{abs}_{A}]$, respectively.
Definition 29 (Exponential of games [18]). The exponential (or of course) $\oc A$ of a game $A$ is defined by: • $M_{\oc A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}M_{A}\times\mathbb{N}$; • $\lambda_{\oc A}:(a,i)\in M_{A}\times\mathbb{N}\mapsto\lambda_{A}(a)$; • $\vdash_{\oc A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{(\star,(\hat{a},i))% \in\{\star\}\times(M_{A}\times\mathbb{N})\mid\star\vdash_{A}\hat{a}\ \!\}\\ \cup\{((a,i),(a^{\prime},i))\in(M_{A}\times\mathbb{N})\times(M_{A}\times% \mathbb{N})\mid a\vdash_{A}a^{\prime}\ \!\}$; • $P_{\oc A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in\mathscr{L}_{\oc A% }\mid\forall i\in\mathbb{N}.\ \!\bm{s}\upharpoonright i\in P_{A}\ \!\}$, where $\bm{s}\upharpoonright i$ is the j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ that consists of moves $(a,i)$ yet changed into $a$; • $\bm{s}\simeq_{\oc A}\bm{t}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{% \Leftrightarrow}}\exists\varphi\in\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{N}).\ \!\forall i\in% \mathbb{N}.\ \!\bm{s}\upharpoonright\varphi(i)\simeq_{A}\bm{t}\upharpoonright i% \wedge\pi_{2}^{\ast}(\bm{s})=(\varphi\circ\pi_{2})^{\ast}(\bm{t})$, where $\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{N})$ is the set of all permutations of natural numbers.
Definition 5 (LLJ [9, 10]). The formal language of ILL is obtained from that of LL by discarding $(\_)^{\bot}$, $\wn$ and $\invamp$. The calculus LLJ for ILL consists of the rules of LLK that have only intuitionistic sequents.
Definition 27 (Linear implication between games [18, 11]). The linear implication $A\multimap B$ from a game $A$ to another $B$ is defined by: • $M_{A\multimap B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}M_{A}+M_{B}$; • $\lambda_{A\multimap B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}[\overline{% \lambda_{A}},\lambda_{B}]$, where $\overline{\lambda_{A}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\langle% \overline{\lambda_{A}^{\mathsf{OP}}},\lambda_{A}^{\mathsf{QA}}\rangle$ and $\overline{\lambda_{A}^{\mathsf{OP}}}(m)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{% =}}\begin{cases}\mathsf{P}&\text{if $\lambda_{A}^{\mathsf{OP}}(m)=\mathsf{O}$}% \\ \mathsf{O}&\text{otherwise}\end{cases}$; • $\vdash_{A\multimap B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{(\star,\hat{b% })\mid\star\vdash_{B}\hat{b}\ \!\}+\{(\hat{b},\hat{a})\mid\star\vdash_{A}\hat{% a},\star\vdash_{B}\hat{b}\ \!\}\\ +(\vdash_{A}\cap\ (M_{A}\times M_{A}))+(\vdash_{B}\cap\ (M_{B}\times M_{B}))$; • $P_{A\multimap B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in\mathscr{% L}_{A\multimap B}\mid\bm{s}\upharpoonright A\in P_{A},\bm{s}\upharpoonright B% \in P_{B}\ \!\}$; • $\bm{s}\simeq_{A\multimap B}\bm{t}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{% \Leftrightarrow}}\bm{s}\upharpoonright A\simeq_{A}\bm{t}\upharpoonright A% \wedge\bm{s}\upharpoonright B\simeq_{B}\bm{t}\upharpoonright B\wedge\mathit{% att}_{A\multimap B}^{\ast}(\bm{s})=\mathit{att}_{A\multimap B}^{\ast}(\bm{t})$, where $\mathit{att}_{A\multimap B}:M_{A\multimap B}\rightarrow\{0,1\}$ maps $a\in M_{A}\mapsto 0,b\in M_{B}\mapsto 1$.
Definition 51 (Why not on games). The why not of a game $A$ is the game $\wn A$ defined by: • $M_{\wn A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init},% \mathbb{N}}+(M_{A}\times\mathbb{N})$, where $M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init},\mathbb{N}}$ is the set of all functions $\mathbb{N}\rightarrow M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}$; • $\lambda_{\wn A}:\alpha\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init},\mathbb{N}}\mapsto\mathsf{OQ},(% a,i)\in M_{A}\times\mathbb{N}\mapsto\lambda_{A}(a)$; • $\vdash_{\wn A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}(\{\star\}\times M_{A}% ^{\mathsf{Init},\mathbb{N}})+(\{\star\}\times(M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times% \mathbb{N}))\\ +\{(\alpha,(a,i))\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init},\mathbb{N}}\times(M_{A}^{\mathsf{% nInit}}\times\mathbb{N})\mid\alpha(i)\vdash_{A}a\ \!\}\\ +\{((a,i),(a^{\prime},i))\in(M_{A}^{\mathsf{nInit}}\times\mathbb{N})^{2}\mid a% \vdash_{A}a^{\prime}\ \!\}$; • $P_{\wn A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in\mathscr{L}_{\wn A% }\mid\forall i\in\mathbb{N}.\ \!\bm{s}\upharpoonright i\in P_{A},\bm{s}=x\bm{t% }\Rightarrow x\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init},\mathbb{N}}\}$, where $\bm{s}\upharpoonright i$ is the j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ that consists of moves $\alpha\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init},\mathbb{N}}$ and $(a,i)\in M_{A}\times\mathbb{N}$ yet changed into $\alpha(i)$ and $a$, respectively; • $\bm{s}\simeq_{\wn A}\bm{t}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{% \Leftrightarrow}}\exists\varphi\in\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{N}).\ \!\forall i\in% \mathbb{N}.\ \!\bm{s}\upharpoonright i\simeq_{A}\bm{t}\upharpoonright\varphi(i% )\wedge(\varphi\circ\mathit{att}_{\wn A})^{\ast}(\bm{s})=\mathit{att}_{\wn A}^% {\ast}(\bm{t})$, where the function $\mathit{att}_{\wn A}:M_{\wn A}\rightarrow\{\star\}+\mathbb{N}$ is given by $\alpha\mapsto\star$ and $(a,i)\mapsto i$.
Definition 20 (Occurrences of moves). Given a finite sequence $\bm{s}\in M_{G}^{\ast}$ of moves of an arena $G$, an occurrence (of a move) in $\bm{s}$ is a pair $(\bm{s}(i),i)$ such that $i\in\overline{|\bm{s}|}$. More specifically, we call the pair $(\bm{s}(i),i)$ an initial occurrence (resp. a non-initial occurrence) in $\bm{s}$ if $\star\vdash_{G}\bm{s}(i)$ (resp. otherwise).
Definition 36 (Copy-cats [17, 41, 31, 18]). The copy-cat (strategy) $\mathit{cp}_{A}$ on a game $A$ is defined by: $\mathit{cp}_{A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in P_{A_{[0]% }\multimap A_{[1]}}^{\mathsf{Even}}\mid\forall\bm{t}\preceq{\bm{s}}.\ \mathsf{% Even}(\bm{t})\Rightarrow\bm{t}\upharpoonright 0=\bm{t}\upharpoonright 1\ \!\}$ where the subscripts $(\_)_{[i]}$ on $A$ are to distinguish the two copies of $A$, and $\bm{t}\upharpoonright i\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\bm{t}% \upharpoonright A_{[i]}$ ($i=0,1$).
Definition 2 (LJ [8, 3]). The calculus LJ for IL consists of the rules of LK that have only intuitionistic sequents, i.e., ones such that the number of formulas on the RHS is $\leqslant 1$.
Definition 32 (Identification of strategies [18]). The identification of strategies on a game $G$, written $\simeq_{G}$, is the relation on strategies $\sigma,\tau:G$ given by $\sigma\simeq_{G}\tau\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{\Leftrightarrow}}% \forall\bm{s}\in\sigma,\bm{t}\in\tau.\ \!\bm{s}m\simeq_{G}\bm{t}l\Rightarrow% \forall\bm{s}mn\in\sigma.\ \!\exists\bm{t}lr\in\tau.\ \!\bm{s}mn\simeq_{G}\bm{% t}lr\wedge\forall\bm{t}lr\in\tau.\ \!\exists\bm{s}mn\in\sigma.\ \!\bm{t}lr% \simeq_{G}\bm{s}mn$. A strategy $\sigma:G$ is valid if $\sigma\simeq_{G}\sigma$.
Definition 45 (Subcategory $\sharp\mathcal{LG}$). The lluf subcategory $\sharp\mathcal{LG}$ of $\mathcal{LG}$ has exactly morphisms $[\phi]$ in $\mathcal{LG}$ such that $\phi$ is strict.
Definition 24 (Legal positions [18, 11]). A legal position of an arena $G$ is a j-sequence $\bm{s}\in\mathscr{J}_{G}$ that satisfies: • (Alternation) $\bm{s}=\bm{s_{1}}mn\bm{s_{2}}\Rightarrow\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{OP}}(m)\neq% \lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{OP}}(n)$; • (Visibility) If $\bm{s}=\bm{t}m\bm{u}$ with $m$ non-initial, then $\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(m)$ occurs in $\lceil\bm{t}\rceil_{G}$ if $m$ is a P-move, and in $\lfloor\bm{t}\rfloor_{G}$ otherwise.
Definition 61 (Strong linearity of strategies). A strategy $\phi:A\multimap B$ is strongly linear if it is linear, strict, and satisfies: 1. If $B=(X_{1}\otimes X_{2})\invamp Y$ for some games $X_{1}$, $X_{2}$ and $Y$, then $\phi=A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi^{\prime}}}{{\multimap}}X_{i}\otimes(X_{j}% \invamp Y)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\Omega}}{{\multimap}}(X_{1}\otimes X_{2})\invamp Y$ for some $\phi^{\prime}:A\multimap X_{i}\otimes(X_{j}\invamp Y)$, where $i\neq j$; 2. If $A=X_{1}\otimes(X_{2}\invamp Y)$ for some games $X_{1}$, $X_{2}$ and $Y$, then $\phi=X_{1}\otimes(X_{2}\invamp Y)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\Omega}}{{\multimap}}(% X_{i}\otimes X_{j})\invamp Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi^{\prime\prime}}}{{% \multimap}}B$ for some $\phi^{\prime\prime}:(X_{i}\otimes X_{j})\invamp Y\multimap B$, where $i\neq j$; 3. If $B=\oc X\invamp\wn Y$ for some games $X$ and $Y$, then $\phi=A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi^{\prime}}}{{\multimap}}\oc(A\invamp\wn Y)% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle\Sigma}}{{\multimap}}\oc X\invamp\wn Y$ for some $A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi^{\prime}}}{{\multimap}}\oc(A\invamp\wn Y)$; 4. If $A=\oc X\otimes\wn Y$ for some games $X$ and $Y$, then $\phi=\oc X\otimes\wn Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\Pi}}{{\multimap}}\wn(\oc A% \invamp Y)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi^{\prime\prime}}}{{\multimap}}B$ for some $\wn(\oc A\invamp Y)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi^{\prime\prime}}}{{\multimap}}B$; 5. If $B=B_{1}\oplus B_{2}$, then $\phi=A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi_{i}}}{{\multimap}}B_{i}\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\iota_{i}}}{{\multimap}}B_{1}\oplus B_{2}$ for some $i\in\overline{2}$ and $\phi_{i}:A\multimap B_{i}$.
Definition 26 (Tensor product of games [18, 11]). The tensor (product) $A\otimes B$ of games $A$ and $B$ is defined by: • $M_{A\otimes B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}M_{A}+M_{B}$; • $\lambda_{A\otimes B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}[\lambda_{A},% \lambda_{B}]$; • $\vdash_{A\otimes B}\ \stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\ \vdash_{A}+\ % \!\vdash_{B}$; • $P_{A\otimes B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in\mathscr{L}% _{A\otimes B}\mid\bm{s}\upharpoonright A\in P_{A},\bm{s}\upharpoonright B\in P% _{B}\ \!\}$, where $\bm{s}\upharpoonright A$ (resp. $\bm{s}\upharpoonright B$) is the j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ that consists of moves of $A$ (resp. $B$); • $\bm{s}\simeq_{A\otimes B}\bm{t}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{% \Leftrightarrow}}\bm{s}\upharpoonright A\simeq_{A}\bm{t}\upharpoonright A% \wedge\bm{s}\upharpoonright B\simeq_{B}\bm{t}\upharpoonright B\wedge\mathit{% att}_{A\otimes B}^{\ast}(\bm{s})=\mathit{att}_{A\otimes B}^{\ast}(\bm{t})$, where $\mathit{att}_{A\otimes B}:M_{A\otimes B}\rightarrow\{0,1\}$ maps $a\in M_{A}\mapsto 0,b\in M_{B}\mapsto 1$.
Definition 49 (Functor par). The functor par is the bifunctor $\invamp$ on $\sharp\mathcal{LG}$ that maps objects $(A,B)\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}\times\sharp\mathcal{LG}$ to $A\invamp B\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}$, and morphisms $([\phi],[\psi])\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}\times\sharp\mathcal{LG}((A,C),(B,D))$ to $[\phi\invamp\psi]\in\sharp\mathcal{LG}(A\invamp C,B\invamp D)$.
Definition 19 (Arenas [18]). An arena is a triple $G=(M_{G},\lambda_{G},\vdash_{G})$, where: • $M_{G}$ is a set whose elements are called moves; • $\lambda_{G}$ is a function from $M_{G}$ to $\{\mathsf{O},\mathsf{P}\}\times\{\mathsf{Q},\mathsf{A}\}$, called the labeling function, in which $\mathsf{O}$, $\mathsf{P}$, $\mathsf{Q}$ and $\mathsf{A}$ are arbitrarily fixed symbols, called the labels; • $\vdash_{G}$ is a subset of $(\{\star\}\cup M_{G})\times M_{G}$, where $\star$ is an arbitrarily fixed element such that $\star\not\in M_{G}$, called the enabling relation, that satisfies: – (E1) $\star\vdash_{G}m$ implies $\lambda_{G}(m)=\mathsf{OQ}\wedge(n\vdash_{G}m\Leftrightarrow n=\star)$; – (E2) $m\vdash_{G}n\wedge\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{QA}}(n)=\mathsf{A}$ implies $\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{QA}}(m)=\mathsf{Q}$; – (E3) $m\vdash_{G}n\wedge m\neq\star$ implies $\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{OP}}(m)\neq\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{OP}}(n)$ in which $\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{OP}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\pi_{1}% \circ\lambda_{G}:M_{G}\to\{\mathsf{O},\mathsf{P}\}$ and $\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{QA}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\pi_{2}% \circ\lambda_{G}:M_{G}\to\{\mathsf{Q},\mathsf{A}\}$. A move $m\in M_{G}$ is initial if $\star\vdash_{G}m$, an O-move (resp. a P-move) if $\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{OP}}(m)=\mathsf{O}$ (resp. if $\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{OP}}(m)=\mathsf{P}$), a question (resp. an answer) if $\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{QA}}(m)=\mathsf{Q}$ (resp. if $\lambda_{G}^{\mathsf{QA}}(m)=\mathsf{A}$). Let $M_{G}^{\mathsf{Init}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{m\in M_{G}% \mid\star\vdash_{G}m\ \!\}$ and $M_{G}^{\mathsf{nInit}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}M_{G}\setminus M% _{G}^{\mathsf{Init}}$.
Definition 35 (Strictness of strategies). A strategy $\phi:A\multimap B$ is strict if $\forall\bm{s}mn\in\sigma.\ \!m\in M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}}\Rightarrow n\in M_{A}^% {\mathsf{Init}}$.
Definition 11 (FwLSMCs). A SMC $\mathcal{C}=(\mathcal{C},\invamp,\bot)$ is forward-liberalizable (FwL) if it has finite coproducts $(0,\oplus)$ and is equipped with: • A monad $\wn=(\wn,\eta,\mu)$ on $\mathcal{C}$ such that the canonical adjunction between $\mathcal{C}$ and the Kleisli category $\mathcal{C}^{\wn}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ over $\wn$ is monoidal; • Isomorphisms $\wn 0\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\rightarrow}}\bot$ and $\wn(A\oplus B)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\rightarrow}}\wn A\invamp\wn B$ natural in $A,B\in\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 42 (Category $\mathcal{LG}$). The category $\mathcal{LG}$ is given by: • Objects are wf-games; • Morphisms $A\rightarrow B$ are the equivalence classes $[\phi]\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\phi^{\prime}:A\multimap B% \mid\phi\simeq_{A\multimap B}\phi^{\prime}\ \!\}$ of valid, winning, linear strategies $\phi:A\multimap B$; • Composition of morphisms $[\phi]:A\rightarrow B$ and $[\psi]:B\rightarrow C$ is given by $[\psi]\circ[\phi]\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}[\psi\circ\phi]:A\rightarrow C$; • Identities are given by $\mathit{id}_{A}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}[\mathit{cp}_{A}]:A\rightarrow A$.
Definition 23 (Views [18]). The Player (P-) view $\lceil\bm{s}\rceil_{G}$ of a j-sequence $\bm{s}\in\mathscr{J}_{G}$ of an arena $G$ is the j-subsequences of $\bm{s}$ given by the following induction on $|\bm{s}|$: $\lceil\bm{\epsilon}\rceil_{G}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\bm{\epsilon}$; $\lceil\bm{s}m\rceil_{G}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\lceil\bm{s}% \rceil_{G}.m$ if $m$ is a P-move; $\lceil\bm{s}m\rceil_{G}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}m$ if $m$ is initial; and $\lceil\bm{s}m\bm{t}n\rceil_{G}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\lceil% \bm{s}\rceil_{G}.mn$ if $n$ is an O-move such that $m$ justifies $n$. The Opponent (O-) view $\lfloor\bm{s}\rfloor_{G}$ of $\bm{s}$ is symmetric to $\lceil\bm{s}\rceil_{G}$.
Definition 56 (LL${}^{-}$ morphisms). Given a BiLSMCC $\mathcal{C}$, a morphism in $\sharp\mathcal{C}$ is LL$\bm{{}^{-}}$ if it is of the following form: $A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\varsigma}}{{\rightarrow}}A^{\prime}\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\phi}}{{\rightarrow}}B^{\prime}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\varrho}}{{% \rightarrow}}B$ such that $\phi$, $\varsigma$ and $\varrho$ are morphisms in $\sharp\mathcal{C}$ inductively constructed respectively by the following grammars: • $\phi\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\mathit{id}\mid\oc^{\top}\mid\oc% ^{\bot}\mid\phi\otimes\phi\mid\phi\invamp\phi\mid\langle\phi,\phi\rangle\mid[% \phi,\phi]\mid\phi;\phi\mid\oc\phi\mid\wn\phi\mid\lambda(\phi)\mid\lambda^{-1}% (\phi)$ • $\varsigma\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\mathit{id}\mid\Omega\mid% \Upsilon\mid\Pi\mid\alpha\mid\ell\mid\varpi\mid\epsilon\mid\delta\mid\theta% \mid\pi_{i}\mid(\ref{NI2})\mid\varsigma\otimes\varsigma\mid\varsigma\invamp% \varsigma\mid\varsigma;\varsigma$ • $\varrho\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\mathit{id}\mid\Omega\mid% \Upsilon\mid\Sigma\mid\alpha\mid\ell\mid\varpi\mid\eta\mid\mu\mid\vartheta\mid% \iota_{i}\mid(\ref{NI1})\mid\varrho\otimes\varrho\mid\varrho\invamp\varrho\mid% \varrho;\varrho$ where $\oc^{\top}$ (resp. $\oc^{\bot}$) is the canonical one to $\top$ (resp. from $\bot$), $\alpha$, $\ell$ and $\varpi$ respectively range over associativities, units and symmetries w.r.t. $\otimes$ or $\invamp$, $\theta$ (resp. $\vartheta$) over natural isomorphisms of $\oc$ (resp. $\wn$), $\pi_{i}$ and $\iota_{i}$ over projections and injections ($i=1,2$), respectively, $\oc=(\oc,\epsilon,\delta)$, $\wn=(\wn,\eta,\mu)$, and $\lambda$ (resp. $\lambda^{-1}$) is currying w.r.t. the entire domain (resp. uncurrying w.r.t. the entire codomain).
Definition 31 (Strategies [18]). A strategy on a game $G$ is a non-empty subset $\sigma\subseteq P_{G}^{\mathsf{Even}}$, written $\sigma:G$, that satisfies: • (S1) Even-prefix-closed (i.e., $\forall\bm{s}mn\in\sigma.\ \!\bm{s}\in\sigma$); • (S2) Deterministic (i.e., $\forall\bm{s}mn,\bm{s^{\prime}}m^{\prime}n^{\prime}\in\sigma.\ \!\bm{s}m=\bm{s% ^{\prime}}m^{\prime}\Rightarrow\bm{s}mn=\bm{s^{\prime}}m^{\prime}n^{\prime}$).
Definition 1 (LK${}^{-}$). The calculus LK$\bm{{}^{-}}$ for CL consists of the rules in Fig. 1.
Definition 28 (Sum of games). The sum $A\oplus B$ of games $A$ and $B$ is defined by: • $M_{A\oplus B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}(M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}% \times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}})+M_{A}+M_{B}$; • $\lambda_{A\oplus B}:(\hat{a},\hat{b})\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{% \mathsf{Init}}\mapsto\mathsf{OQ},a\in M_{A}\mapsto\lambda_{A}(a),b\in M_{B}% \mapsto\lambda_{B}(b)$; • $\vdash_{A\oplus B}\ \stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{(\star,(\hat{a% },\hat{b}))\mid\star\vdash_{A}\hat{a},\star\vdash_{B}\hat{b}\ \!\}+\vdash_{A}+% \vdash_{B}\\ +\{((\hat{a},\hat{b}),a)\in(M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}})% \times M_{A}\mid\hat{a}\vdash_{A}a\ \!\}\\ +\{((\hat{a},\hat{b}),b)\in(M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}})% \times M_{B}\mid\hat{b}\vdash_{B}b\ \!\}$; • $P_{A\oplus B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in\mathscr{L}_% {A\&B}\mid\bm{s}\upharpoonright A\in P_{A}\vee\bm{s}\upharpoonright B\in P_{B}% ,\bm{s}=x\bm{t}\Rightarrow x\in(M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf{% Init}})\cap(P_{A}\times P_{B})\}$, where $\bm{s}\upharpoonright A$ (resp. $\bm{s}\upharpoonright B$) is the j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ that consists of moves $(\hat{a},\hat{b})\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}}$ and $a\in M_{A}$ (resp. $b\in M_{B}$) with the former changed into $\hat{a}$ (resp. $\hat{b}$); • $\bm{s}\simeq_{A\oplus B}\bm{t}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{% \Leftrightarrow}}\bm{s}\upharpoonright A\simeq_{A}\bm{t}\upharpoonright A\vee% \bm{s}\upharpoonright B\simeq_{B}\bm{t}\upharpoonright B$.
Definition 38 (Composition of strategies [18]). Given games $A$, $B$ and $C$, and strategies $\phi:A\multimap B$ and $\psi:B\multimap C$, the parallel composition $\phi\parallel\psi$ of $\phi$ and $\psi$ is given by: $\displaystyle\phi\parallel\psi$ $\displaystyle\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in\mathscr{J}_% {((A\multimap B_{[0]})\multimap B_{[1]})\multimap C}\mid\bm{s}\upharpoonright A% ,B_{[0]}\in\phi,$ $\displaystyle\bm{s}\upharpoonright B_{[1]},C\in\psi,\bm{s}\upharpoonright B_{[% 0]},B_{[1]}\in\mathit{pr}_{B}\ \!\}$ where the subscripts $(\_)_{[i]}$ on $B$ ($i=0,1$) are to distinguish the two copies of $B$, $\bm{s}\upharpoonright A,B_{[0]}$ (resp. $\bm{s}\upharpoonright B_{[1]},C$, $\bm{s}\upharpoonright B_{[0]},B_{[1]}$) is the j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ that consists of moves of $A$ or $B_{[0]}$ (resp. $B_{[1]}$ or $C$, $B_{[0]}$ or $B_{[1]}$), and $\mathit{pr}_{B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in P_{B_{[0]% }\multimap B_{[1]}}\mid\forall\bm{t}\preceq{\bm{s}}.\ \mathsf{Even}(\bm{t})% \Rightarrow\bm{t}\upharpoonright 0=\bm{t}\upharpoonright 1\ \!\}$. The composition $\phi;\psi$ (or $\psi\circ\phi$) of $\phi$ and $\psi$ is defined by: $\phi;\psi\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\upharpoonright A,C% \mid\bm{s}\in\phi\!\parallel\!\psi\ \!\}$ where $\bm{s}\upharpoonright A,C$ is the j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ that consists of moves of $A$ or $B$.
Definition 21 (J-sequences [18]). A justified (j-) sequence of an arena $G$ is a pair $\bm{s}=(\bm{s},\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}})$ of a finite sequence $\bm{s}\in M_{G}^{\ast}$ and a map $\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}:\overline{|\bm{s}|}\rightarrow\{0\}\cup\overline{|\bm{s}|% -1}$ such that for all $i\in\overline{|\bm{s}|}$ $\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(i)=0$ if $\star\vdash_{G}\bm{s}(i)$, and $0<\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(i)<i\wedge\bm{s}({\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(i)})\vdash_{G}% \bm{s}(i)$ otherwise. The occurrence $(\bm{s}({\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(i)}),\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}}(i))$ is called the justifier of a non-initial occurrence $(\bm{s}(i),i)$ in $\bm{s}$.
Definition 52 (Why not on strategies). The why not of a strategy $\phi:A\multimap B$ is the subset $\wn\phi\subseteq P_{\wn A\multimap\wn B}^{\mathsf{Even}}$ given by: $\wn\phi\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in P_{\wn A\multimap% \wn B}^{\mathsf{Even}}\mid\forall i\in\mathbb{N}.\ \!\bm{s}\upharpoonright i% \in\phi\ \!\}$ where $\bm{s}\upharpoonright i$ is the obvious analogue of that given in Def. 51.
Definition 25 (Games [18, 11]). A game is a quintuple $G=(M_{G},\lambda_{G},\vdash_{G},P_{G},\simeq_{G})$ such that $(M_{G},\lambda_{G},\vdash_{G})$ is an arena, $P_{G}$ is a non-empty, prefix-closed subset of $\mathscr{L}_{G}$, whose elements are called (valid) positions of $G$, and $\simeq_{G}$ is an equivalence relation on $P_{G}$, called the identification of (valid) positions of $G$, that satisfies: • (I1) $\bm{s}\simeq_{G}\bm{t}\Rightarrow|\bm{s}|=|\bm{t}|$; • (I2) $\bm{s}m\simeq_{G}\bm{t}n\Rightarrow\bm{s}\simeq_{G}\bm{t}\wedge\lambda_{G}(m)=% \lambda_{G}(n)\wedge(m,n\in M_{G}^{\mathsf{Init}}\vee(\exists i\in\overline{|% \bm{s}|}.\ \!\mathcal{J}_{\bm{s}m}(m)=\bm{s}(i)\wedge\mathcal{J}_{\bm{t}n}(n)=% \bm{t}(i)))$; • (I3) $\bm{s}\simeq_{G}\bm{t}\wedge\bm{s}m\in P_{G}\Rightarrow\exists\bm{t}n\in P_{G}% .\ \!\bm{s}m\simeq_{G}\bm{t}n$.
Definition 47 (Par on games). The par of games $A$ and $B$ is the game $A\invamp B$ defined by: • $M_{A\invamp B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}(M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}% \times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}})+M_{A}+M_{B}$; • $\lambda_{A\invamp B}:(\hat{a},\hat{b})\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{% \mathsf{Init}}\mapsto\mathsf{OQ},a\in M_{A}\mapsto\lambda_{A}(a),b\in M_{B}% \mapsto\lambda_{B}(b)$; • $\vdash_{A\invamp B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{(\star,(\hat{a}% ,\hat{b}))\mid\star\vdash_{A}\hat{a},\star\vdash_{B}\hat{b}\ \!\}+\vdash_{A}+% \vdash_{B}\\ +\{((\hat{a},\hat{b}),a)\in(M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}})% \times M_{A}\mid\hat{a}\vdash_{A}a\ \!\}\\ +\{((\hat{a},\hat{b}),b)\in(M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}})% \times M_{B}\mid\hat{b}\vdash_{B}b\ \!\}$; • $P_{A\invamp B}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\bm{s}\in\mathscr{L}% _{A\invamp B}\mid\bm{s}\upharpoonright A\in P_{A},\bm{s}\upharpoonright B\in P% _{B},\bm{s}=x\bm{t}\Rightarrow x\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf% {Init}}\}$, where $\bm{s}\upharpoonright A$ (resp. $\bm{s}\upharpoonright B$) is the j-subsequence of $\bm{s}$ that consists of moves $(\hat{a},\hat{b})\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}}$ and $a\in M_{A}$ (resp. $b\in M_{B}$) with the former changed into $\hat{a}$ (resp. $\hat{b}$); • $\bm{s}\simeq_{A\invamp B}\bm{t}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{% \Leftrightarrow}}\mathit{att}_{A\invamp B}^{\ast}(\bm{s})=\mathit{att}_{A% \invamp B}^{\ast}(\bm{t})\wedge\bm{s}\upharpoonright A\simeq_{A}\bm{t}% \upharpoonright A\wedge\bm{s}\upharpoonright B\simeq_{B}\bm{t}\upharpoonright B$, where $\mathit{att}_{A\invamp B}$ is the function $M_{A\invamp B}\rightarrow\{0,1,2\}$ that maps $(\hat{a},\hat{b})\in M_{A}^{\mathsf{Init}}\times M_{B}^{\mathsf{Init}}\mapsto 0% ,a\in M_{A}\mapsto 1,b\in M_{B}\mapsto 2$.
Definition 14 (Distributive laws [29]). Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category, and $\wn=(\wn,\eta,\mu)$ and $\oc=(\oc,\epsilon,\delta)$ a monad and a comonad on $\mathcal{C}$. A distributive law of $\oc$ over $\wn$ is a natural transformation $d:\oc\wn\Rightarrow\wn\oc$ such that $\wn\epsilon\circ d=\epsilon\wn:\oc\wn\Rightarrow\wn$, $\wn\delta\circ d=d\oc\circ\oc d\circ\delta\wn:\oc\wn\Rightarrow\wn\oc\oc$, $d\circ\oc\eta=\eta\oc:\oc\Rightarrow\wn\oc$ and $d\circ\oc\mu=\mu\oc\circ\wn d\circ d\wn:\oc\wn\wn\Rightarrow\wn\oc$.
Definition 33 (Winning of strategies). A strategy $\sigma:G$ is: • Total if $\bm{s}\in\sigma\wedge\bm{s}m\in P_{G}$ implies $\exists\bm{s}mn\in\sigma$ [42, 43]; • Innocent if $\bm{s}mn,\bm{t}\in\sigma\wedge\bm{t}m\in P_{G}\wedge\lceil\bm{t}m\rceil_{G}=% \lceil\bm{s}m\rceil_{G}$ implies $\bm{t}mn\in\sigma\wedge\lceil\bm{t}mn\rceil_{G}=\lceil\bm{s}mn\rceil_{G}$ [31, 18, 11]; • Noetherian if $\sigma$ does not contain any strictly increasing infinite sequence of P-views of positions of $G$ [42]; • Winning if it is innocent, total and noetherian. In addition, an innocent strategy $\sigma:G$ is finite if the set $\lceil\sigma\rceil_{G}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{df.}}}{{=}}\{\lceil\bm{s}% \rceil_{G}\mid\bm{s}\in\sigma\ \!\}$ of all P-views of $\sigma$ is finite.
Definition 3.4. By a finite covering11of course, “finite covering” does not refer to a covering family for some topology with finitely many morphisms (“finite cover” would be a better name for this notion). Here, the morphisms themselves have to be finite - and in the affine case, one reduces to the case of a single such morphism. of an affine $k$-scheme $X$, we mean a finite surjective morphism $Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\to}}X$ in ${\bf{Aff}}_{k}$.
Definition 9.1. An affine Noetherian $k$-scheme $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,R$ is called a splinter if every finite covering (equivalently, any covering for the finite topology) is a canonical covering.
Definition 2.2. [NP, Definition 2.6] Let $\delta=(A,\delta,C),\delta^{\prime}=(A^{\prime},\delta^{\prime},C^{\prime})$ be any pair of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions. Let $C\overset{\iota_{C}}{\longrightarrow}C\oplus C^{\prime}\overset{\iota_{C^{% \prime}}}{\longleftarrow}C^{\prime}$ and $A\overset{p_{A}}{\longleftarrow}A\oplus A^{\prime}\overset{p_{A^{\prime}}}{% \longrightarrow}A^{\prime}$ be coproduct and product in $\mathcal{B}$, respectively. Since $\mathbb{E}$ is biadditive, we have a natural isomorphism $\mathbb{E}(C\oplus C^{\prime},A\oplus A^{\prime})\cong\mathbb{E}(C,A)\oplus% \mathbb{E}(C,A^{\prime})\oplus\mathbb{E}(C^{\prime},A)\oplus\mathbb{E}(C^{% \prime},A^{\prime}).$ Let $\delta\oplus\delta^{\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(C\oplus C^{\prime},A\oplus A^{\prime})$ be the element corresponding to $(\delta,0,0,\delta^{\prime})$ through the above isomorphism. This is the unique element which satisfies $\displaystyle\mathbb{E}(\iota_{C},p_{A})(\delta\oplus\delta^{\prime})=\delta$ $\displaystyle,$ $\displaystyle\mathbb{E}(\iota_{C},p_{A^{\prime}})(\delta\oplus\delta^{\prime})% =0,$ $\displaystyle\mathbb{E}(\iota_{C^{\prime}},p_{A})(\delta\oplus\delta^{\prime})=0$ $\displaystyle,$ $\displaystyle\mathbb{E}(\iota_{C^{\prime}},p_{A^{\prime}})(\delta\oplus\delta^% {\prime})=\delta^{\prime}.$
Definition 1.1. Let $(\mathcal{C},\mathbb{E},\mathfrak{s})$ be an extriangulated category, and $\mathcal{Q},\mathcal{W},\mathcal{R}$ three classes of objects in $\mathcal{C}$. (1) $\mathcal{W}$ is called thick if it is closed under direct summands and satisfies the $2$-out-of-$3$ property: for any $\mathbb{E}$-triangle $A\overset{}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{}{\longrightarrow}C\overset{}{\dashrightarrow}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ with two terms in $\mathcal{W}$, the third term belongs to $\mathcal{W}$ as well. (2) A triple $(\mathcal{Q},\mathcal{W},\mathcal{R})$ is called extriangulated model structures if $(\mathcal{Q},\mathcal{W}\cap\mathcal{R})$ and $(\mathcal{Q}\cap\mathcal{W},\mathcal{R})$ are two cotorsion pairs and $\mathcal{W}$ is thick. In this case, a triple $(\mathcal{Q},\mathcal{W},\mathcal{R})$ is also called Hovey.
Definition 2.1. [NP, Definition 2.3] Let $(A,\delta,C),(A^{\prime},\delta^{\prime},C^{\prime})$ be any pair of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions. A morphism $(a,c)\colon(A,\delta,C)\to(A^{\prime},\delta^{\prime},C^{\prime})$ of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions is a pair of morphisms $a\in\mathcal{C}(A,A^{\prime})$ and $c\in\mathcal{C}(C,C^{\prime})$ in $\mathcal{C}$, satisfying the equality $a_{\ast}\delta=c^{\ast}\delta^{\prime}.$ Simply we denote it as $(a,c)\colon\delta\to\delta^{\prime}$.
Definition 9.3. Let $F$ be a facet. We call $\alpha$ a root of the stabilizer $W(F)$ if there exists an integer $n_{\alpha}$ such that $(\alpha,x)=n_{\alpha}\ell$ for every $x\in F$. We call a root $\alpha$ positive if $(\alpha,x)>0$ for all $x\in F$. Finally, we call a collection $R_{F}^{+}=\{\alpha_{i}\}$ of positive roots of $W(F)$ a set of simple roots of $F$ if every positive root of $W(F)$ can be uniquely written as a linear combination of the $\alpha_{i}$s with nonnegative integer coefficients.
Definition 8.1. ([O97] [An04]) For $\lambda,\mu\in X^{+}$ write $\lambda\leq_{q}\mu$ if there exists $Q\in Tilt(U_{q}(\mathfrak{g}),{\mathbb{Q}}(q))$ such that $T(\lambda)$ is a summand of $T(\mu)\otimes Q$. If both $\lambda\leq_{q}\mu$ and $\mu\leq_{q}\lambda$ write $\lambda\sim_{q}\mu$. The equivalence classes are called weight cells.
Definition 9.1. Let $\ell$ be a positive integer, $\ell>n$, and let $s$ be the number of columns of $\lambda$. Then we write the expression $(i-1)\ell+x_{j-1}$ into the box of $\lambda$ in the $i$-th row and $j$-th column, where we have the convention $0=x_{0}<x_{1}<\ ...\ <x_{s-1}<\ell$. The standard facet $F_{0}(\lambda)$ consists of all $n$-tuples whose coordinates consist of all possible arrangements of numbers in the boxes of $\lambda$, written in descending order.
Definition 2.1. a) Let $I\subset R$ be an ideal. We call a morphism $f:X\to Y$ $I$-negligible if $Tr_{X}(g\circ f)\in I$ and $Tr_{Y}(f\circ g)\in I$ for all morphisms $g:Y\to X$. An object $X$ is called $I$-negligible if $Tr_{X}(a)\in I$ for all $a\in{\rm End}(X)$. b) If $f$ is $I$-negligible with respect to $I=\mathfrak{m}^{k}$, we simply say that $f$ is $k$-negligible. An object is $k$-negligible if it is $I$-negligible for $I=\mathfrak{m}^{k}$.
Definition 8.10. Let $F_{1}$ and $F_{2}$ be minimal facets. We say that they are tensor equivalent if $\mathcal{I}(F_{1})=\mathcal{I}(F_{2})$.
Definition 9.5. Let $y$ be a point in the interior or lower closure of a given alcove. We call a subset $\{y_{i},i\in I\}$ of the coordinates of $y$ a $y$-chain if $|y_{i}-y_{j}|\geq\ell$ for all $i,j\in I$. We call it an $\ell$-strict (or just strict) $y$-chain if its elements are of the form $y_{i}-r\ell$ for $0\leq r<|I|-1$.
Definition 3.1. If $I$ is a thick ideal in $\mathcal{C}$ then a trace on $I$ is a family of linear functions $\{\operatorname{\mathsf{t}}_{V}:{\rm End}_{\mathcal{C}}(V)\rightarrow R\}$ where $V$ runs over all objects of $I$ and such that following two conditions hold. (1) If $U\in I$ and $W\in\mathcal{C}$ then for any $f\in{\rm End}_{\mathcal{C}}(U\otimes W)$ we have $\operatorname{\mathsf{t}}_{U\otimes W}\left(f\right)=\operatorname{\mathsf{t}}% _{U}\left(\operatorname{t}_{R}(f)\right).$ (2) If $U,V\in I$ then for any morphisms $f:V\rightarrow U$ and $g:U\rightarrow V$ in $\mathcal{C}$ we have $\operatorname{\mathsf{t}}_{V}(g\circ f)=\operatorname{\mathsf{t}}_{U}(f\circ g).$
Definition 9.2. We call a facet $F$ strongly minimal if $F^{\prime}\not<F$ for any $F^{\prime}$ with $W(F^{\prime})\cong W(F)$. Here all facets are assumed to be in the interior of $C$.
